
## Create the Makefile

Inside your project root directory, create a file named **Makefile** (no extension).

```bash
touch Makefile
```

On Windows (CMD):

```cmd
type nul > Makefile
```

---

## Paste This Makefile Content

```makefile
# ===============================
# Git Automation Makefile
# ===============================

REPO_URL = https://github.com/USERNAME/REPOSITORY.git
BRANCH = main
WHAT ?= "update"

# Initialize git repository
init:
	git init
	git branch -M $(BRANCH)
	git remote add origin $(REPO_URL)

# Check git status
status:
	git status

# Add all files
add:
	git add .

# Commit changes
commit:
	git commit -m $(WHAT)

# Push to GitHub
push:
	git push -u origin $(BRANCH)

# Pull latest changes
pull:
	git pull origin $(BRANCH)

# Full workflow (add + commit + push)
deploy:
	git add .
	git commit -m $(WHAT)
	git push origin $(BRANCH)

# Show remotes
remote:
	git remote -v
```

---

## Update Repository URL

Replace:

```makefile
REPO_URL = https://github.com/USERNAME/REPOSITORY.git
```

With your actual GitHub repository URL.

---

## How to Use the Makefile

### Initialize Git (only once)

```bash
make init
```

---

### Check Status

```bash
make status
```

---

### Add Files

```bash
make add
```

---

### Commit With Custom Message

```bash
make commit WHAT="initial commit"
```

---

### Push to GitHub

```bash
make push
```

---

### One-Command Deploy (Most Used)

```bash
make deploy WHAT="fixed auth bug"
```

This runs:

* `git add .`
* `git commit`
* `git push`

---

## 5Requirements (Important)

* Use **Git Bash** on Windows (Makefile does not work well in CMD)
* Ensure `make` is installed

  * Git Bash usually includes it
  * If not, install via **Chocolatey** or **MSYS2**

---

## 6Optional: .gitignore Reminder

Create `.gitignore`:

```
.env
node_modules/
vendor/
*.log
dist/
build/
```

---

## 7Why This Is Good for You

* Faster workflow
* Consistent commits
* Clean automation
* Scales well for team projects and CI/CD

---
